Low-income voters are more likely to identify as Democrats while high-income voters are more likely to identify as Republicans.[304] In 2012, Obama won 60% of voters with income under $50,000 and 45% of those with incomes higher than that.[305] Bush won 41% of the poorest 20% of voters in 2004, 55% of the richest twenty percent and 53% of those in between. In the 2006 House races, the voters with incomes over $50,000 were 49% Republican while those with incomes under that amount were 38% Republican.[302]
